"title": "7707: apostles, designation of",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "7707",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>An apostle is one who is “sent” by Jesus Christ. The word is used to refer especially to the inner circle of Christ's twelve disciples, but is also used specifically to refer to Paul, who was commissioned as an apostle by the risen Christ. The term is also applied more loosely to certain other leading Christians in the NT period.</p>\n<h2>Jesus Christ as an apostle</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb3:1\">HEB 3:1</a></strong> <em>This is the only place where the word “apostle” is used of Jesus Christ, though many passages refer to him as “sent”</em>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John20:21\">JHN 20:21</a></strong> <em>Jesus Christ, as God's “sent one”, sets the standard and pattern for all who are likewise “sent” (i.e., for all apostolic ministry).</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt10:40\">MAT 10:40</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark9:37\">MRK 9:37</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John5:23-John5:24\">JHN 5:23–5:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John12:44-John12:45\">JHN 12:44–12:45</a></p>\n<h2>The twelve apostles called by Jesus Christ</h2>\n<h3>Their appointment</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark3:13-Mark3:19\">MRK 3:13–3:19</a></strong> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt10:1-Matt10:4\">MAT 10:1–10:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke6:12-Luke6:16\">LUK 6:12–6:16</a></p>\n<h3>Their number</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John6:70\">JHN 6:70</a></strong> <em>“the Twelve” is frequently used to designate these specially chosen disciples. The number twelve evokes the twelve tribes of Israel.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt19:28\">MAT 19:28</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt20:17\">MAT 20:17</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark11:11\">MRK 11:11</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke8:1\">LUK 8:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts6:2\">ACT 6:2</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor15:5\">1CO 15:5</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev21:14\">REV 21:14</a></p>\n<h3>Their commissioning by the risen Christ</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt28:18-Matt28:20\">MAT 28:18–28:20</a></strong></p>\n<h3>The replacement for Judas</h3>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts1:15-Acts1:26\">ACT 1:15–1:26</a> <em>The symbolic number (twelve) is thus preserved.</em></p>\n<h3>The qualifications for being an apostle</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts1:21-Acts1:22\">ACT 1:21–1:22</a></strong></p>\n<h2>Paul as an apostle</h2>\n<h3>His self-designation</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal1:1\">GAL 1:1</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom1:1\">ROM 1:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor1:1\">1CO 1:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Tim2:7\">1TI 2:7</a></p>\n<h3>His commissioning by Jesus Christ</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts26:12-Acts26:18\">ACT 26:12–26:18</a> <em>Although not one of the Twelve, Paul saw the risen Christ and was directly commissioned by him, sent especially to the Gentiles</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor15:3-1Cor15:10\">1CO 15:3–15:10</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal2:8\">GAL 2:8</a></p>\n<h3>Paul's apostleship and the church</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor9:1-1Cor9:2\">1CO 9:1–9:2</a></strong> <em>In Paul's case the sense of title or office and the ministry and function virtually coincide. He is an apostle both because he has seen and been commissioned by the risen Christ and because he functioned as an apostle by founding churches.</em></p>\n<h2>Other apostles</h2>\n<h3>Barnabas</h3>\n<p>Here <code>apostles'' may refer to their ministry as missionary evangelists or to their role as</code>sent'' by the church at Antioch:\n <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts14:4\">ACT 14:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts14:14\">ACT 14:14</a></p>\n<h3>James, the Lord's brother</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor15:7\">1CO 15:7</a> <em>The most natural meaning of the words is that James is an apostle. This interpretation is confirmed by other references to James</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal1:19\">GAL 1:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal2:9\">GAL 2:9</a></p>\n<h3>Andronicus and Junias</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom16:7\">ROM 16:7</a></p>\n<h3>Silas</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Thess2:6\">1TH 2:6</a></p>\n<h3>``Apostles'' of the churches</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor8:23\">2CO 8:23</a> <em>“representatives” is the translation here for “apostles”</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Phil2:25\">PHP 2:25</a> <em>“messenger” is the translation here for “apostle”</em></p>\n<h2>False apostles</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor11:5\">2CO 11:5</a> <em>Paul ironically refers to his opponents as “super-apostles”</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor11:13\">2CO 11:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor12:11\">2CO 12:11</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev2:2\">REV 2:2</a></p>",
